Title : Jacob Wit
Text : '''Jacob Wit''' (born 24 December 1952, in [[Haarlemmermeer]]) is a justice of the [[Caribbean Court of Justice]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Achong|first=Derek|title=CCJ calls for change in immigration laws|url=https://www.guardian.co.tt/news/2013-10-05/ccj-calls-change-immigration-laws|work=Trinidad & Tobago Guardian Online|accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref> located in [[Trinidad and Tobago]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Maarten|first=Sint|title=GS of Ombudsman office Sxm concludes exchange visit to Trinidad and Barbados|url=http://www.sxmislandtime.com/component/k2/item/18074-gs-of-ombudsman-office-sxm-concludes-exchange-visit-to-trinidad-and-barbados.html|work=St. Maarten Island Time.com|accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref> Since 2010 he also serves as the President of the [[Constitutional Court of Sint Maarten]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Van der veer|first=Ron|title=Judge Bob Wit will lead Public Administration Integrity Committee|url=http://www.sxmislandtime.com/island-times/island-legal/26065-judge-bob-wit-will-lead-public-administration-integrity-committee.html|work=St. Maarten Island Times|accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref> and is a former Judge of the Rotterdam District Court<ref>{{cite web|title=Prime Minister Meets with Justice Jacob Wit.|url=http://www.smn-news.com/st-maarten-st-martin-news/10171-prime-minister-meets-with-justice-jacob-wit.html|work=St. Martin News Network|accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref> and the [[Common Court of Justice of the Netherlands Antilles and Aruba]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Prime Minister Meets with Justice Jacob Wit.|url=http://www.smn-news.com/st-maarten-st-martin-news/10171-prime-minister-meets-with-justice-jacob-wit.html|work=St. Martin News Network|accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref>

== Early life and legal career ==

Wit (Netherlands Antilles) was born on 24 December 1952 in [[Haarlemmermeer]], [[Netherlands]].

He graduated from the [[Pius X Lyceum]] ([[Amsterdam]]) in 1971, entering in that same year the [[Vrije Universiteit]] (Free University) of Amsterdam, from which he took the degree of [[Master of Laws]] with honours in 1977.<ref>{{cite web|title=THE HONOURABLE MR. JUSTICE JACOB WIT|url=http://www.caribbeancourtofjustice.org/about-the-ccj/judges/wit|work=Caribbean Court of Justice Official Web Site|publisher=Caribbean Court of Justice|accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref> After completing his military service (1976-1978) as a Second Lieutenant in the [[Royal Dutch Navy]].<ref>{{cite web|title=THE HONOURABLE MR. JUSTICE JACOB WIT|url=http://www.caribbeancourtofjustice.org/about-the-ccj/judges/wit|work=Caribbean Court of Justice Official Web Site|publisher=Caribbean Court of Justice|accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref> Wit was admitted in March 1978 as a Judicial Trainee at the [[Studiecentrum Rechtspleging]] (Training and Study Centre for the Judiciary) in [[Zutphen]], where he remained until 1984.<ref>{{cite web|title=Prime Minister Meets with Justice Jacob Wit.|url=http://www.smn-news.com/st-maarten-st-martin-news/10171-prime-minister-meets-with-justice-jacob-wit.html|work=St. Martin News Network|accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref> During this period, he held the posts of [[Law Clerk]] in the Rotterdam District Court, [[Rotterdam]], (1978-1980) and Deputy Prosecutor at the Amsterdam District Court (1980-1982) and worked as an [[attorney-at-law]] with the Law Firm of [[Van Doorne & Sjollema]] in [[Rotterdam]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Prime Minister Meets with Justice Jacob Wit.|url=http://www.smn-news.com/st-maarten-st-martin-news/10171-prime-minister-meets-with-justice-jacob-wit.html|work=St. Martin News Network|accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref>

== Judicial career ==

Wit was appointed as Deputy Judge of the Rotterdam District Court in January 1984, Judge of the Netherlands Antilles and Aruba on 1 October 1986 where he functioned as Coordinating Judge, Court of First Instance, Curaçao (1993-1996); Coordinator Judge of Instruction, Netherlands Antilles (1994-1997); Coordinating Judge for the Dutch Windward Islands of Sint Maarten, Sint Eustatius and Saba and from 2001 to 2005 as Senior Justice and Acting Chief Justice.<ref>{{cite web|title=Prime Minister Meets with Justice Jacob Wit.|url=http://www.smn-news.com/st-maarten-st-martin-news/10171-prime-minister-meets-with-justice-jacob-wit.html|work=St. Martin News Network|accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref>
He took the Oath of Office as a Judge of the [[Caribbean Court of Justice]] (CCJ) at the President’s House [[Port of Spain]], on Wednesday 1 June 2005.<ref>{{cite web|title=Prime Minister Meets with Justice Jacob Wit.|url=http://www.smn-news.com/st-maarten-st-martin-news/10171-prime-minister-meets-with-justice-jacob-wit.html|work=St. Martin News Network|accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref> In November 2010, Wit was appointed and sworn in as the President of the [[Constitutional Court of Sint Maarten]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Prime Minister Meets with Justice Jacob Wit.|url=http://www.smn-news.com/st-maarten-st-martin-news/10171-prime-minister-meets-with-justice-jacob-wit.html|work=St. Martin News Network|accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref> a part-time function.

